Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Coronavirus (COVID-19) cases have been confirmed in Trinidad and Tobago. The Trinbagonian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Local measures
On 6 April, the Trinidad and Tobago government extended “stay at home” orders, for the non-essential labour force, for an additional period of 15 days until 30 April. The Trinidad and Tobago government has also introduced the immediate mandatory wearing of masks, to cover noses and mouths, in public spaces. All British nationals in Trinidad and Tobago should adhere to all precautionary measures put in place by the local authorities.
Schools and universities are also closed until 30 April.
The Trinidad and Tobago government has set up a COVID-19 hotline staffed by doctors. If you suspect you have any symptoms please contact the hotline on 877-WELL (9355). You should not report to any healthcare facility but instead self-quarantine and follow instructions provided by the authorities.
Travel restrictions
On 21 March the Trinidad and Tobago government announced the indefinite closure of its borders to all international flights effective midnight 22 March.
The Trinidad and Tobago authorities previously introduced a ban on the entry of non-nationals after midnight on Tuesday 17 March.
For information on how to return to the UK from Trinidad and Tobago, see Return to the UK.
All international arrivals into Trinidad and Tobago are required to self-isolate for a period of 14 days. Further information and guidance is available at www.health.gov.tt.
Temperature screening is in place at the airport.
The Trinidad and Tobago authorities have announced a ban on cruise ships entering until the end of the current cruise season.
Local measures
Schools and universities are closed until 20 April.
The Trinidad and Tobago authorities have set up a hotline if you have coronavirus symptoms or concerns about your risk of exposure to coronavirus. The number to call is +1 868 877-WELL (9355).
